A special difficulty about ‘void’ must be noticed here. Inane (κενόν) is used by Lucr., following Epicurus, to denote two different things: (1) empty space; (2) space, in which bodies rest, properly called locus (τόπος), or through which bodies move, properly called spatium (χώρα). In fact, both locus and spatium are sometimes in- clusive, and sometimes exclusive, of the bodies contained in them: for the former, cf. l. 523 and see n. to l. 969.
